            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Mateo Rojas-Smith is a product of two San Franciscos. Born in the Mission District to Elena Rojas, a fiercely dedicated community activist from a Mexican-American family, and David Smith, a quiet, intellectual English professor, Mateo\u2019s childhood was a blend of grassroots organizing and literary discussion. He grew up in the vibrant, chaotic Mission of the 70s and 80s, witnessing both the power of community and the devastating onset of the AIDS crisis and gentrification. This duality defined him.\n\nInitially wanting to escape his mother's shadow, he flirted with literature at SF State but found himself inexorably drawn to the social issues surrounding him. The stories he heard in his neighborhood were more compelling than any book. This realization was his first major turning point, leading him to pursue a Master of Social Work at UC Berkeley. He started his career as a frontline case manager, working with unhoused populations and families in crisis. Over two decades, he steadily rose through the ranks, his quiet competence and deep empathy earning him the respect of his peers.\n\nThe death of his mother ten years ago was another profound shift. It was no longer about following her path, but about carrying her legacy forward. As Program Director at a Haight-Ashbury community health center, he now fights battles in boardrooms and grant applications, securing funding for the very services he once provided. He lives in a rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Richmond with his partner of 15 years, Sarah, a public school teacher. Their life is a partnership built on shared values and a commitment to public service.\n\nHis daily routine is simple: a morning coffee with Sarah, a 2.5-mile bike ride through the Panhandle to work, and long days navigating bureaucracy to help people. Mateo\u2019s connection to San Francisco is etched into his soul\u2014he loves its fog-draped parks and radical history but fears for its future. His dream isn\u2019t of wealth, but of sustainability: securing permanent funding for a youth mental health program. He aspires not to change the world, but to hold his small, vital corner of it together."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe is eight years old, his small hand lost in his mother\u2019s. They are marching down Mission Street, protesting tenant evictions. The air smells of exhaust and the carnitas from a nearby cart. He doesn\u2019t understand the politics, only the roar of the crowd and the fierce, protective grip of his mother\u2019s fingers. In that moment, nestled in the chanting throng, he feels a surge of pride and belonging. Community wasn\u2019t an idea; it was a physical force, a wall of people standing together, and his mother was at its heart.\n\n2.\nIn the hushed quiet of the SF State library, sophomore year, he stared at a page of Faulkner, the words blurring. He couldn\u2019t focus. All he could hear was the conversation from the taqueria the night before\u2014a family, their voices low and panicked, discussing a rent increase they couldn\u2019t possibly pay. The ink on the page felt inert, lifeless. The family\u2019s fear was terrifyingly real. It was a clear, silent thunderclap in his mind: the stories he needed to engage with weren't in books. They were on the street, just blocks away.\n\n3.\nAs a rookie case manager, he sat on the floor of a Tenderloin family shelter, a box of crayons between him and a six-year-old girl who hadn\u2019t spoken since her family was evicted. While her mother quietly wept, he just drew, coloring a ridiculously bright sun. The girl finally picked up a blue crayon and drew a small, wobbly house next to his sun. The immense weight of her silent trauma, and that tiny act of trust, settled in his bones forever. It taught him his job wasn't to solve, but to hold space.\n\n4.\nA month after his mother\u2019s funeral, he found her old grant proposal binders from the 80s. Her passionate, almost frantic, notes were scrawled in the margins, fighting for every dollar for a free clinic. In her careful budgets and defiant arguments, he didn\u2019t see a shadow to escape, but a blueprint. The torch wasn\u2019t just passed; he realized he was already carrying it. His own work in drab offices, fighting for funding, was the same fight, just in a different language. The grief began to feel like fuel.\n\n5.\nThis morning, like most, the fog was a soft gray wall outside their Inner Richmond window. Sarah handed him his mug, her fingers warm against his for a second. They stood in comfortable silence, watching the mist drift. Fifteen years, and this simple ritual was his anchor. Her quiet strength, her belief in him and their shared work, was the silent engine that powered him through the exhausting days. This partnership was his sustainability, the reason he had the fortitude to fight for everyone else's."
